definition.value: An integrative interaction network process of an organism that starts from the moment when the first cell forms, has its blueprint stored in the genotype, and performs its dynamic process by interacting with its environment to achieve its survival and other motivations.

The state that distinguishes organisms from inorganic matter, manifested by growth, metabolism, reproduction, and adaptation. It includes the course of existence, the sum of experiences, the mode of existing, or the fact of being. Over the centuries inquiries into the nature of life have crossed the boundaries from philosophy to biology, forensic medicine, anthropology, etc., in creative as well as scientific literature.

A characteristic that distinguishes physical entities that have biological processes, such as signaling and self-sustaining processes, from those that do not, either because such functions have ceased (they have died), or because they never had such functions and are classified as inanimate. Various forms of life exist, such as plants, animals, fungi, protists, archaea, and bacteria.

There is currently no consensus regarding the definition of life. One popular definition is that organisms are open systems that maintain homeostasis, are composed of cells, have a life cycle, undergo metabolism, can grow, adapt to their environment, respond to stimuli, reproduce and evolve. Other definitions sometimes include non-cellular life forms such as viruses and viroids.

A modern Pagan religion developed in Europe during the early 20th century. Its practitioners model it on the pre-Christian belief systems adhered to by the Nordic peoples of the Iron Age and Early Middle Ages.

A modern Pagan religion developed in Europe during the early 20th century. Its practitioners model it on the pre-Christian belief systems adhered to by the Anglo-Saxon peoples of the Iron Age and Early Middle Ages.

Collective representations of acceptable group conduct as well as individual perceptions of particular group conduct. They can be viewed as cultural products (including values, customs, and traditions) which represent individuals' basic knowledge of what others do and think that they should do. From a sociological perspective, social norms are informal understandings that govern the behavior of members of a society.
Any type of modern paganism or contemporary pagan movement based on the ancient Celtic religion.
An esoteric and racialist religion pioneered by Guido von List and Jörg Lanz von Liebenfels respectively, in Austria between 1890 and 1930.
A white supremacist racial religion promulgated by David Lane, based on the exoteric doctrine of Ariosophy, which took the form of popular myths intended for the lower social classes.

A form of white nationalist modern paganism which was founded in the early 1990s by Ron McVan, Katja Lane and David Lane (1938–2007) while Lane was serving a 190-year prison sentence for his actions in connection with the white supremacist revolutionary domestic terrorist organization The Order, of which he was a member.
Any of various forms of Germanic neopaganism with racialist beliefs, especially those that are white nationalist.

Any of a group of racialist (usually white nationalist) Germanic neopagan religions and/or movements which define themselves as "modern-day" expressions of ancient religions which grew and evolved with the Indo-European peoples who settled in Northern Europe and came to be known as "Germanic".
A North American variant of Anglo-Saxon neopaganism. The first known Theod group was formed in Watertown, New York in 1976.
A religion related to Armanism which is based on a Germanic deity Irmin supposedly reconstructed from literaric, linguistic and onomastic sources.
Any of various modern Pagan religion developed in Scandinavia during the early 20th century.
Any of various racialist American sects of Germanic neopaganism (and their descendants, which may or may not be racialized) which claim to be Ásatrú or otherwise worship the Germanic Æsir.
Depending on the context, Ásatrú may be considered more moderate (versus more right-wing extremist forms of Germanic racial neopaganism, like Odinism).
A form of racialized Nazi-affiliated form of Germanic neopaganism, which prioritizes the odal rune (hence the name).
Any of various forms of Anglo-Saxon neopaganism with racialist beliefs, especially those that are white nationalist.
A racialized form of Anglo-Saxon neopaganism, particularly that practiced by the England-based group Woden's Folk, which believes that Adolf Hitler was the reincarnation of the god Woden.
Any of various forms of Anglo-Saxon neopaganism without racialist significant beliefs.
A thought or patterns of thought in which an individual generates a belief or beliefs in a conspiracy theory.

An explanation for an event or situation that invokes a conspiracy by sinister and powerful groups, often political in motivation, when other explanations are more probable. The term has a negative connotation, implying that the appeal to a conspiracy is based on prejudice or insufficient evidence.
An idea or a collection of ideas that departs significantly from the prevailing or mainstream view.

A political and social philosophy promoting traditional social institutions in the context of culture and civilization. The central tenets of conservatism include tradition, hierarchy, and authority, as established in respective cultures, as well as property rights. Conservatives seek to preserve a range of institutions such as organized religion, parliamentary government, and property rights, with the aim of emphasizing continuity. Adherents of conservatism often oppose modernism and seek a return to "the way things were".

A political ideology characterized by respect for American traditions, republicanism, limited government, support for Christian values, moral universalism, pro-business, opposition to trade unions, strong national defense, free trade, protectionism, anti-communism, rugged individualism, advocacy of American exceptionalism, and a defense of tradition and Western culture from the perceived threats posed by communism, socialism, and moral relativism.

A term for the political ideology, style of governance, political movement, and/or set of mechanisms for acquiring and keeping power that are associated with Donald Trump, the 45th President of the United States (2017–2021), and his political base. It is an American politics version of the right-wing to far-right, national-populist sentiment seen in multiple nations worldwide and holds some aspects of illiberal democracy.
Any of various behaviors considered destructive.

Any of various behaviors in which one has a tendency to do harm to oneself, either as a direct or indirect result of their actions; frequently marked by impulse, but also includes chronic, injurious behaviors.
Behavior in which persons hurt or harm themselves without the motive of suicide or of sexual gratification.

A form of self-abuse on the internet. It is usually done by teenagers posting fake insults on social media, attacking themselves to elicit attention and sympathy, however it may take many other forms.
A form of conservatism which claims to be based in various tenants of the Christian faith. Such ideologies often overlap with Christian fundamentalism and conservative evangelicalism.
One of the major branches of anthropology, focusing on society and culture.
The study of patterns of behaviour in human societies and cultures.
The branch of anthropology that compares and analyzes the characteristics of different peoples and the relationships between them.

A branch of anthropology and the systematic study of individual cultures. In contrast with ethnology, ethnography explores cultural phenomena from the point of view of the subject of the study. Ethnography is also a type of social research involving the examination of the behaviour of the participants in a given social situation and understanding the group members' own interpretation of such behavior.

A form of qualitative research in which an author uses self-reflection and writing to explore anecdotal and personal experience and connect this autobiographical story to wider cultural, political, and social meanings and understandings.
A surgical procedure in which a uterus is transplanted from one organism to another, typically in cases in which the uterus is absent or diseased.
A surgical procedure in which a cervix is transplanted from one organism to another, typically in cases in which the cervix is absent or diseased.
